Trim and halve the @green beans{80%grams}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated with garlic press). Zest and halve the @lime{1}.

Pour the @water for the rice{300%milliliter} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting lid.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%grams} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%grams} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Stir in the @North Indian style spice mix{1%sachet} and garlic. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%milliliter}, @ketjap manis{25%grams}, @soy sauce{15%milliliter}, @water for the curry{50%milliliter}, @sugar{1%tsp} and the green beans, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat slightly and simmer until the sauce has thickened, the beans are tender and the chicken is cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the curry is cooked, stir in half the lime juice.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of @?water{} if it's a little thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest.

When ready, share the zesty rice between your #bowls{}.

Top with the chicken curry and serve with the remaining lime wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!